<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSS Methods Example</title>

    <!-- Internal CSS: Body background color -->
    <style>
        /* Body styles */
        body {
            background-color: lightblue; /* Set the body background to light blue */
        }

        /* Header styles */
        h1 {
            color: red; /* All h1 headings will be red */
        }
    </style>
    
    <!-- External stylesheet link -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>

    <h1 style="color: red;">This heading is red via inline style</h1> <!-- Inline CSS for h1 -->
    
    <p>This is a paragraph that uses internal and external styles.</p>
    
</body>
</html>

EXTERNAL CSS
/* External stylesheet for reusable styles */

/* Body styles */
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

/* Header styles */
h1 {
    font-size: 2em;
    font-weight: bold;
}

/* Paragraph styles */
p {
    font-size: 1.2em;
    line-height: 1.5;
}


Summary of Pros and Cons:
Inline CSS:
Pros: Quick and easy to apply to individual elements.
Cons: Not reusable; makes HTML cluttered and harder to maintain.
Internal CSS:
Pros: Suitable for small projects or single-page websites; easier to manage than inline styles.
Cons: Can lead to duplication if used across multiple pages; harder to scale.
External CSS:
Pros: Most efficient for large projects; keeps HTML clean and separate from styling; reusable across multiple pages.
Cons: Requires an additional HTTP request to fetch the stylesheet, though this is minimal with modern caching.
By using external CSS for reusable styles, internal CSS for page-specific styles, and inline CSS for individual element overrides, you can manage styles in a flexible and efficient manner. Let me know if you need further clarifications or improvements!



